Specifically, the underlying data set, which can be found [here](https://fiscaldata.treasury.gov/datasets/average-interest-rates-treasury-securities/average-interest-rates-on-u-s-treasury-securities), reports the Average Interest Rate Amount for the Security Type Description "Interest-bearing Debt" with the Security Description being "Total Interest-bearing Debt." For the end of Fiscal Year 2024, dated 9/30/24, this was 3.324 percent.&#x20;

For purposes of this question, the US government's fiscal year will be considered to run from October 1st of the preceding calendar year to September 30th of the named year, aligning with [current reported US government practices](https://www.usa.gov/federal-budget-process). For example, FY 2028 will be considered to run from October 1, 2027 to September 30, 2028 and will resolve based on the average interest rate amount paid on total interest-bearing debt recorded on (or closest to) September 30, 2028.&#x20;

If the resolution value is less than the left bound or greater than the right bound, it resolves as outside the respective bound rather than a specific number.&#x20;

If the resolution source moves or is removed, Metaculus may use a new resolution source, as long as its methodology is judged by Metaculus to be substantially similar to the current resolution source. It should include both marketable and non-marketable treasury securities and should report the percentage paid by the US government based on aggregate interest payments divided by total amount of debt.&#x20;

